        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>596</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">misc-000K</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>misc-000K.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Myhill–Nerode automaton">Myhill–Nerode automaton</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Construction</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>22</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link type="local" href="trebor.xml" addr="trebor" title="Trebor">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For any language <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L} \subseteq  \Sigma ^*]]></fr:tex>, the <fr:strong>Myhill–Nerode automaton</fr:strong> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> is a deterministic automata (possibly with infinitely many states) that recognizes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex>. The language <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> is regular iff there are only finitely many <fr:link type="local" href="misc-000J.xml" addr="misc-000J" title="Nerode congruence">Nerode congruence</fr:link> classes of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex>. In this case, the automaton is the unique minimal DFA for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>586</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#248</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-248.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>22</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link type="local" href="trebor.xml" addr="trebor" title="Trebor">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>We define the states of the automaton be the Nerode congruence classes. For each letter <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  \Sigma ]]></fr:tex>, we add a transition between the congruence classes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[x]]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[xa]]]></fr:tex>. This is well-defined and deterministic by definition of the congruence. It is also obvious that a DFA for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> cannot have less states.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
